summary: I love Killing Eve SO much. I have been waiting for a likable female psychopath for AGES. Ages. And T-Swift said it well by...
body: I love Killing Eve SO much. I have been waiting for a likable female psychopath for AGES. Ages. And T-Swift said it well by calling Villanelle “endearing” – that her badassery is endearing, and that is EXACTLY it. It is a villainy that is cool and likable and sympathetic and attractive. The whole show is just so COOL and so female-dominated but not in a pandering way, just in a normal way, and that’s what sells it for me. I don’t think I’ve ever seen a female villain that I have well and truly liked like this, like, ever. Male villains have had the space to be cool, but I’ve never seen that with female villains. Villanelle is so dimensional. She isn’t purely evil, but she is so evil. She’s a grown woman, but also a child – she’s sexy but also does the most repulsive things imaginable. And then Eve, who is an amazing character in her own right, is our eyes, the audience’s eyes, and she’s no saint either – she’s safely allowed to be obsessed with this morally-corrupt woman and so. Are. We. In the same way Batman was allowed to be obsessed with the Joker. It’s SO good.

summary: Villanelle’s Best Outfit Yet
title: Villanelle’s Best Outfit Yet
body:
Villanelle’s, empress of fashion and murder, best outfit shows up in Season 2, Episode 5. She starts out preparing to mourn her paramour in a silky jet black pantsuit; an appetizer so good that even the bellhop feels sorry for her. 

Work on your headpatting, bellhop. SOFTER!

But then: the main dish is served. Our melodramatic murderess shows up at Eve’s house in full Victorian mourning regalia. 

And no Eve, you may not take her veil! 

Some friendly knifeplay and arsenic tasting later (a hell of a fourth date), Villanelle and Eve arrive in the forest of black ops. Without her veil, Villanelle looks utterly like a witch from a fairytale. The dynamic here is interesting because it is not Villanelle leading Eve into temptation, into the darkness of the woods and the human psyche. Eve, looking like a huntress, is offering Villanelle the proverbial apple. As we saw with Eve on the metro station milaseconds away from pushing a man into the oncoming train, Eve is no longer wrestling with her internal darkness. She has accepted it and wants to explore it with her one and only, of course. 

My favorite shot of our fairytale femme fatale in the woods. I love the sweep of the skirt. 


Bonus outfit: Villanelle shows up to Oxford to bully Niko in the most pretentious, posh and British outfit ever. The silk tie. The corded sweater over the shoulders. The wide trousers. The only thing more Oxford than Oxford is Villanelle.

Smell ya later, Niko.
